Larynx cancer in Germany: solution

Matteo Fasiolo, Simon N. Wood

2023-10-06

  1. Load data and fit a Poisson GAM with MRF smooth:
library(testGam)
library(mgcv)
data("Larynx")
data("german.polys")

X <- t(sapply(german.polys, colMeans, na.rm=TRUE))

fit1 <- gam(Y ~ s(region, k = 200, bs="mrf", xt=list(polys=german.polys)) + 
                offset(log(E)) + s(x, k=20),
            family=poisson, 
            data=Larynx)

plot(fit1, ask = FALSE)

  1. Now use an isotropic TPS smooth, and plot the bi-variate effect using two different schemes:
fit2 <- gam(Y ~ s(X[,1], X[,2], k = 200) + offset(log(E)) + s(x,k=20), 
            family = poisson, data = Larynx)

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(fit2, select = 1)
plot(fit2, select = 1, scheme = 2)

  1. Now we use a tensor-product smooth:
fit3 <- gam(Y~te(X[,1],X[,2],k=c(15, 15))+offset(log(E))+s(x,k=20), 
            family=poisson, data=Larynx)

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(fit3, select = 1)
plot(fit3, select = 1, scheme = 2)

We now compare the three models in terms of AIC

AIC(fit1, fit2, fit3)
##            df      AIC
## fit1 62.12100 2743.201
## fit2 48.56910 2753.095
## fit3 41.36673 2752.972

The MRF model is better in terms of AIC.

  1. This will give an error
tryCatch(gam.check(fit3), 
         error = function(e) print(e))
## 
## Method: UBRE   Optimizer: outer newton
## full convergence after 4 iterations.
## Gradient range [-1.09891e-07,6.075584e-07]
## (score 0.1005984 & scale 1).
## Hessian positive definite, eigenvalue range [0.0006117273,0.009427392].
## Model rank =  244 / 244 
## 
## <simpleError in names(dat) <- object$term: 'names' attribute [2] must be the same length as the vector [0]>

To solve this we must add the variables use in the model formula to the data.frame

Larynx$lon <-  X[,1]
Larynx$lat <-  X[,2]

fit3 <- gam(Y~te(lon, lat,k=c(15, 15))+offset(log(E))+s(x,k=20), 
            family=poisson, data=Larynx)

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
gam.check(fit3)

vis.gam(fit3, view = c("lon", "lat"), theta = 210, phi = 40 )
